Oseney Abbey, founded iu 1129 by Robert d’Oilg'i. The story of its foundation is told by leland as follows :-

‘Robert Oilley had a wife caullid Edithe Fome, a woman of same ¹ and highly esteemed by King Henry 1. This Robert began the priorie of blake chanons at Oseney in Oxsord among the isles that Isis ryver ther makyth. Sum write that this was the occasion os making of it. Edith usid to walke out os Oxsord Castelle with her gentlewomen to solace, and that ofteutymes wher in a certen place in a tree as osten as she cam, certen Pyes usid to gither to it, and ther to chattre, and as it wer, to sp‘eke on to her. Edithe much mervelyng at this mattier aud was sum tyme sore ferid as by a wonder, whereupon she sent for one Radulphe a chonon of S. Frideswyde, a man of a vertuous life and her consessor, uskiug him eounsell ; to whom he auswerid, aster that he had sene the faschion of the Pyes chatteriug only at her cummyng; “O Madam these are no Pyes, but so many lost soules in purgatory, that doe begge and make this complaint for succour aud relies, and they knowing you to be pityfull and oue that will have regard of their condition, doe direct their clamours to yon, hoping that by your charity you would bestow something both worthy of their relief and also for the welfare of your's aud your posteritye's soules.'' These wordes being finish't she replied “Audis it soi wa de Pardieuxi if old Robin my husband will concede to my nequest Ishall doe my best endeavour to be a means to bring these wretched soules to rest.'' And thereupon relatiug. the whole matter to her husband did soe much (by her continuall and frequent importunitys to him) bring the business about’ -and amid “chinkingrivulets and shady groves audwalks encompassiug it ” the Priory was built.
